(suspenseful music)

188
00:15:21,380 --> 00:15:22,980
- On the sixth floor, huh?

189
00:15:26,740 --> 00:15:28,320
But which one is his?

190
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:38,540
- Good evening, why don't you please come inside?

191
00:15:41,380 --> 00:15:43,380
Make yourself at home, have a seat.

192
00:15:45,760 --> 00:15:46,280
(footsteps)

193
00:15:50,180 --> 00:15:52,420
- So you want to meet him too, don't you?

194
00:15:53,080 --> 00:15:53,820
- Meet who?

195
00:15:54,700 --> 00:15:56,000
- I'm waiting for him as well.

196
00:15:56,360 --> 00:15:57,240
He'll be here soon.

197
00:15:58,420 --> 00:16:00,000
Since we've got some time to spare,

198
00:16:00,120 --> 00:16:01,160
let's talk about something.

199
00:16:01,640 --> 00:16:03,380
What would be good to talk about?

200
00:16:04,300 --> 00:16:05,760
Oh, I've got it.

201
00:16:06,200 --> 00:16:08,560
Why don't we talk about the end of the world?

202
00:16:11,140 --> 00:16:13,800
- The young man continued talking cheerfully.

203
00:16:15,560 --> 00:16:20,220
He was like a kid telling his parents about how much fun he had that day at school.

204
00:16:23,720 --> 00:16:25,540
That was how he talked to me.

205
00:16:28,120 --> 00:16:30,520
End of the world? Please.

206
00:16:31,020 --> 00:16:33,240
Just a crazy maniac spouting nonsense.

207
00:16:34,060 --> 00:16:35,560
That's what I thought at the time.

208
00:16:38,100 --> 00:16:40,880
What do you think? It's interesting, isn't it?

209
00:16:41,260 --> 00:16:43,880
Have I piqued your curiosity yet, Mr. Martin?

210
00:16:45,560 --> 00:16:48,360
Hold on a second, kid. How do you know my name?

211
00:16:49,940 --> 00:16:53,240
I just know. Now let's talk all about you, shall we?

212
00:16:53,840 --> 00:16:56,620
You've worked for the baby for three years, haven't you?

213
00:16:57,300 --> 00:16:59,160
What? Did you look into my background?

214
00:16:59,700 --> 00:17:02,560
Before that, you served time in prison for eight years.

215
00:17:02,680 --> 00:17:04,040
That must have been awful for you.

216
00:17:04,480 --> 00:17:06,460
You were released early for good behavior.

217
00:17:06,680 --> 00:17:09,720
For a guy that got convicted of murder, you certainly got out quickly.

218
00:17:10,280 --> 00:17:11,640
Did you like living with your girlfriend?

219
00:17:12,140 --> 00:17:13,460
I'm pretty sure you did.

220
00:17:13,980 --> 00:17:16,160
I'm talking about the girlfriend you shot.

221
00:17:16,620 --> 00:17:18,140
Her name was... Eda?

222
00:17:18,820 --> 00:17:21,260
I think it's pretty rude of you to talk about her.

223
00:17:21,860 --> 00:17:24,080
That Eda was quite the drug addict, wasn't she?

224
00:17:24,320 --> 00:17:27,560
And you did your best to try and keep her off the stuff, didn't you?

225
00:17:27,880 --> 00:17:30,320
Goodness, that's a pretty difficult thing to pull off.

226
00:17:31,200 --> 00:17:32,980
Were you... in love then?

227
00:17:33,620 --> 00:17:35,460
Were you asking me for a beating?

228
00:17:35,900 --> 00:17:37,460
Then she quit the drug somehow.

229
00:17:37,940 --> 00:17:40,840
All was bliss and she would wait for you to come home every night.

230
00:17:40,840 --> 00:17:43,120
Together, the two of you were quite happy.

231
00:17:43,460 --> 00:17:46,020
Are you asking for a beating? Answer me.

232
00:17:46,420 --> 00:17:49,200
But then one night, when you returned to your room,

233
00:17:49,300 --> 00:17:51,600
you saw something that really made your blood boil.

234
00:17:52,500 --> 00:17:55,220
There she was, with her old boyfriend.

235
00:17:57,920 --> 00:18:01,620
She'd been doing drugs again. It was written all over her face.

236
00:18:01,980 --> 00:18:04,060
But once she saw you standing there,

237
00:18:04,400 --> 00:18:07,940
all she could do was say the same thing over and over.

238
00:18:07,940 --> 00:18:13,760
I'm sorry. I'm sorry. I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.

239
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:18,720
But you shot her, along with her ex-boyfriend.

240
00:18:19,120 --> 00:18:22,600
That was your story at the trial, after all. Why'd you lie?

241
00:18:23,120 --> 00:18:25,180
That doesn't make a whole lot of sense.

242
00:18:26,800 --> 00:18:29,540
The truth was, she killed herself.

243
00:18:30,320 --> 00:18:33,620
Your lawyer figured out from the lab reports that she shot herself.

244
00:18:34,060 --> 00:18:36,660
They found traces of gunpowder on her right hand.

245
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:41,460
You stuck to the story that you gunned her down.

246
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:45,720
Tell the truth. She literally begged you to kill her, didn't she?

247
00:18:47,320 --> 00:18:50,660
Ha! Am I right? I'm dead on, aren't I?

248
00:18:50,940 --> 00:18:53,000
I knew you weren't the one who shot her!

249
00:18:53,780 --> 00:18:56,740
And she really was begging you to shoot her, wasn't she?

250
00:18:56,940 --> 00:18:58,560
Oh, I could just see it.

251
00:19:00,240 --> 00:19:02,000
Please, Martin, shoot me.

252
00:19:04,440 --> 00:19:06,080
Please don't look at me like that.

253
00:19:06,580 --> 00:19:07,580
Shoot me now!

254
00:19:07,940 --> 00:19:09,400
I want you to kill me!

255
00:19:11,620 --> 00:19:12,120
Martin!

256
00:19:26,680 --> 00:19:27,920
It wasn't me!

257
00:19:28,120 --> 00:19:29,320
She did it to herself!

258
00:19:29,620 --> 00:19:30,760
I didn't shoot her, man!

259
00:19:31,280 --> 00:19:31,720
(panting)

260
00:19:37,180 --> 00:19:37,620
See?

261
00:19:37,820 --> 00:19:38,940
It was me, right?

262
00:19:39,380 --> 00:19:39,740
Right?

263
00:19:42,660 --> 00:19:43,100
(gunshot)

264
00:19:46,560 --> 00:19:48,880
- Isn't it amazing that I was able to figure it out?

265
00:19:48,960 --> 00:19:50,080
I'm right, aren't I?

266
00:19:50,440 --> 00:19:51,340
- You're wrong.

267
00:19:51,840 --> 00:19:53,640
- You made the decision to leave her behind.

268
00:19:54,100 --> 00:19:56,640
And by doing that, you gave her just what she wanted.

269
00:19:56,900 --> 00:19:57,580
- Like hell.

270
00:19:57,880 --> 00:19:58,480
- I'm right.

271
00:19:58,480 --> 00:19:59,960
It was the same with your mother!

272
00:20:02,520 --> 00:20:04,340
Your mother froze to death.

273
00:20:04,560 --> 00:20:07,160
She died unexpectedly when you were ten years old.

274
00:20:07,540 --> 00:20:10,260
You've got a long history of abandoning women, don't you?

275
00:20:11,780 --> 00:20:13,620
Ha ha! I'm right again!

276
00:20:13,980 --> 00:20:15,340
I knew it! Amazing!

277
00:20:15,780 --> 00:20:17,920
I really have a gift for this! What a skill!

278
00:20:18,920 --> 00:20:23,100
Every night, your mother would get stinking drunk and you'd carry her home.

279
00:20:23,340 --> 00:20:24,120
Isn't that right?

280
00:20:24,340 --> 00:20:27,580
And your mother would always tell you to just leave her where she was.

281
00:20:28,480 --> 00:20:34,420
the street, but you wouldn't listen. Instead, you'd carry her home every time. But then

282
00:20:34,420 --> 00:20:35,900
came that one night.

283
00:20:36,760 --> 00:20:39,700
No, Mom. It's too cold. You can't sleep out here.

284
00:20:39,700 --> 00:20:44,100
This weather's fine. Stop falling on me. Just lay me right here.

285
00:20:50,060 --> 00:20:51,680
Mom, wake up!

286
00:21:08,880 --> 00:21:14,140
You left her there. Isn't that true? You left your mother there.

287
00:21:14,700 --> 00:21:19,100
The next day, the police came to your house and told you that your mother had frozen to death.

288
00:21:19,640 --> 00:21:21,800
You thought that what happened wasn't your fault.

289
00:21:22,260 --> 00:21:26,220
After all, you had left her there because she told you to.

290
00:21:26,220 --> 00:21:28,940
And you're right. It wasn't your fault.

291
00:21:29,460 --> 00:21:32,860
Your mother and your girlfriend both wanted to die.

292
00:21:33,140 --> 00:21:36,600
You were helping people who wanted to die to find some relief.

293
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:39,420
Why torture yourself? You did the right thing.

294
00:21:39,800 --> 00:21:43,340
Look, you freed the two of them from the agonies of their worthless lives.

295
00:21:46,720 --> 00:21:50,600
Now there's Ava. She too wishes to die, Martin.

296
00:22:02,320 --> 00:22:06,420
It was at that moment that the devil arrived.

297
00:22:08,100 --> 00:22:12,000
I walked by the devil, careful not to look.

298
00:22:13,680 --> 00:22:23,760
Like a child, I repeated to myself, "Don't look, don't look, don't you dare look."

299
00:22:40,300 --> 00:22:41,700
[MUSIC]

300
00:23:38,300 --> 00:23:39,700
[MUSIC]

301
00:23:44,940 --> 00:23:46,360
(upbeat music)

